'Hydrogen iodide' (HI) is a diatomic molecule. Aqueous solutions of HI are known
as 'hydroiodic acid' or 'hydriodic acid', a strong acid. Hydrogen iodide and
hydroiodic acid are, however, different in that the former is a gas under
standard conditions; whereas, the other is an aqueous solution of said gas. They
are interconvertible. HI is used in organic and inorganic synthesis as one of
the primary sources of iodine and as a reducing agent.
